Dunno if this should be in [here](https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript-TmLanguage) instead, but as it is theme related (only, I think), I made it here.

- VSCode Version: 1.7.1
- OS Version: Win10 x64

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Typescript file, Monokai theme
2. Make a class with a function, use the `this` and `super` keyword, etc.
3. Recognize the lack of proper highlighting.

Quite a lot of things where changed between 1.6 and 1.7(.1), including the `=>` in lambdas being blue instead of red now, most methods being green when calling them (but sometimes they are blue, like `getAll`, `get`, `set`, `push`, `forEach`, `navigate`, `apply`, `sub`, `sup`, `anchor`, `big`, etc), some fields being blue (but not all; i.e. `x`, `y`, `z`, `length`, `title`, `all`, and `id` are blue, all of `console`'s methods, all of `document`'s methods, etc), and some lonely keywords being blue as well (i.e. `event`; I can understand the blue-ing of `document` and `console`).

A couple other issues I found was with the `instanceof` operator; `foo instanceof String` makes `String` blue (same with `Array`), whereas in `foo instanceof Class` (where Class is a user-made class) `Class` is still a standard white; not even an underlined green!

**I understand these are kind of standard with highlighting, as is shown by the markdown highlighted sample code below**. So perhaps not all of this is bugged, but only really these:
- Using the tick-strings and the `${var}` replacement is not colored correctly.
- Lambda `=>`'s are currently blue, they were red before
- `this` and `super` are standard white, previously they were purple.

Sample code:
```ts
class Parent {

    protected alpha: {[key: string]: number} = { 'hi': 200 };

    public bar(): void {
        console.log('hi');
    }
}

export class Class extends Parent {

    constructor(private parent: Parent) { super(); }

    fus = {
        ro: {
            da: (): void => {
                console.log('*shouts*');
            }
        }
    }

    public foo(): boolean {

        let event = null;
        event = undefined;

        let a: any = { };
        if(a instanceof String) console.log('instanceof string');
        else if(a instanceof Parent) console.log(`instanceof ${"parent"}`);
        var x = a.normal.keys.x.y.z.length.id.title.event.all.getAll().get().set().push().forEach().navigate().apply().sub().sup().anchor().big().normal().methods();

        this.fus.ro.da();
        super.bar();

        return false;
    }
}
```
